com.google.cloud.pubsub.deprecated

Class SubscriptionInfo

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.google.cloud.pubsub.deprecated.SubscriptionInfo
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Subscription

    public class SubscriptionInfo
extends Object
implements Serializable
    A Google Cloud Pub/Sub subscription. A subscription represents the stream of messages from a single, specific topic, to be delivered to the subscribing application. Pub/Sub subscriptions support both push and pull message delivery.

    In a push subscription, the Pub/Sub server sends a request to the subscriber application, at a preconfigured endpoint (see PushConfig). The subscriber's HTTP response serves as an implicit acknowledgement: a success response indicates that the message has been succesfully processed and the Pub/Sub system can delete it from the subscription; a non-success response indicates that the Pub/Sub server should resend it (implicit "nack").

    In a pull subscription, the subscribing application must explicitly pull messages using one of PubSub.pull(String, int), PubSub.pullAsync(String, int) or PubSub.pullAsync(String, PubSub.MessageProcessor callback, PubSub.PullOption...). When messages are pulled with PubSub.pull(String, int) or PubSub.pullAsync(String, int) the subscribing application must also explicitly acknowledge them using one of PubSub.ack(String, Iterable), PubSub.ack(String, String, String...), PubSub.ackAsync(String, Iterable) or PubSub.ackAsync(String, String, String...).

    See Also:
    Pub/Sub Data Model, Subscriber Guide, Serialized Form

        @Deprecated
public TopicId topic()
        Deprecated. 
        Returns the identity of the topic this subscription refers to. If TopicId.project() is null the topic is assumed to reside in the ServiceOptions.getProjectId() project. After a topic is deleted, existing subscriptions to that topic are not deleted, but their topic field is set to TopicId.deletedTopic().

      • ackDeadlineSeconds

        @Deprecated
public long ackDeadlineSeconds()
        Deprecated. 
        Returns the maximum time after a subscriber receives a message before the subscriber should acknowledge the message. After message delivery but before the ack deadline expires and before the message is acknowledged, it is an outstanding message and will not be delivered again during that time (on a best-effort basis). For pull subscriptions, this value is used as the initial value for the ack deadline. To override the ack deadline value for a given message, use PubSub.modifyAckDeadline(String, int, TimeUnit, Iterable). For push delivery, this value is used to set the request timeout for the call to the push endpoint. This value must be between 10 and 600 seconds, if not specified, 10 seconds is used.

      • getAckDeadlineSeconds

        public long getAckDeadlineSeconds()
        Returns the maximum time after a subscriber receives a message before the subscriber should acknowledge the message. After message delivery but before the ack deadline expires and before the message is acknowledged, it is an outstanding message and will not be delivered again during that time (on a best-effort basis). For pull subscriptions, this value is used as the initial value for the ack deadline. To override the ack deadline value for a given message, use PubSub.modifyAckDeadline(String, int, TimeUnit, Iterable). For push delivery, this value is used to set the request timeout for the call to the push endpoint. This value must be between 10 and 600 seconds, if not specified, 10 seconds is used.
